"Abstract In previous articles I have commented on the new United Kingdom Data Protection Act 1998, on the protection and confidentiality of data on the Internet (particularly in relation to data flows to the United States) and on the possible control/censorship of online material. None of those articles more than touched on the more serious but connected issue of the way in which the law deals with children on the Internet and how information about children is handled or controlled. Clearly there are many aspects to this question and I shall endeavour to deal with some of them in this article. Although to Internet afficionados, it may be trite to remind readers that in legal terms the Internet is no different from any other medium, I think that it does no harm to remind oneself that, from a philosophical perspective, the way in which children’s rights are applied (or abused) on the Internet is no different from the way these same issues are dealt with in terrestrial law enforcement. See: http://news2.this.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/newsid%5f2170007217770.stm for an example of cross Atlantic co-operation in this field. Certainly, the global and intrinsically secret nature of the Internet may afford opportunities of access to children by those persons wishing to do them harm — moral, emotional or physical. This article is not intended to be apologist for those people; there may be arguable reasons why adults of sound mind should be permitted (whether under the guise of the First Amendment or similar) to access material which some parts of society might consider not to its taste. Such arguments cannot exist in relation to children (or in relation to those of less than full mental capability)."
